Hypopygium
(
Fig. 1E
). Anal point short and cone-shaped, wide at the base, bearing 20 moderately thick setae; anal point 13–23, 20 μm long, 43–77, 61 μm wide at the base and 18–40, 30 μm wide medially. Virga absent. Two diagonal, lateral sclerites present at the apex of the aedeagal region, just below the sternapodeme. Penis cavity well-sclerotized and appearing as a bifid arched sclerite. Sternapodeme slightly arched, appearing narrow, oral projections thick (
Figs. 1E
; 
6C
), sternapodeme 90–127, 109 μm long. Phallapodeme 74–93, 86 μm long. Inferior volsella blunt (
Figs. 1E
; 
6G
). Gonostylus well expanded in mid to anterior section with outer corner or projection; crista dorsalis developed, stretching from mid to anterior of gonostylus but only visible at certain orientations (
Fig. 1F–G
); gonostylus 100–134, 118 μm long. Gonocoxite 202–230, 220 μm long. HR 1.6–2.1, 1.9, HV 2.6–3.6, 3.1.

Genitalia
(
Fig. 2D–E
). Gonocoxite very long, slightly passing the posterior part of segment IX, bearing close to 20 setae. Seminal capsules large and nearly circular without detectable neck, spermathecal ducts without loops (
Fig. 2D
), seminal capsule 105–136, 125 µm long, 82–118, 103 µm wide. Notum 127–134, 130 µm long, notum and ramus 206–234, 218 µm long. Gonapophysis VIII divided into large ventrolateral lobe covering the base of smaller dorsomesal lobe. The apodeme lobe indistinct, however, large. Tergite IX not divided, though a slight mid-section notch is present, crescent-shaped, bearing 20–26, 24 setae posteriorly (
Fig. 2E
). Sternite IX with 13 setae posteriorly. Cercus small (
Fig. 2E
), 72–107, 92 µm long and 55–87, 67 µm wide.

Figs. 4 A–F
; 
9A, C, E–F

Labro-epipharyngeal region
(
Fig. 4B
). Labral seta SI weakly plumose, with lateral dissections; in some specimens, the SI appears to be simple, but this may be due to the orientation of the setae; labral setae SII and SIII simple, lamelliform; SIV well developed (
Fig. 4B
). Pecten epipharyngis consists of 3 peg-like scales, 8 pairs of chaetulae laterales in two rows or layers of 4 (
Fig. 4B
). Two pairs of bifid chaetulae basales. Premandible with a wide apical tooth and a broad inner tooth, 67–87, 76 μm long (
Fig. 4B
).

Abdomen
(
Fig. 4E–F
; 
9C, E–F
). Procercus 8–14, 10 μm long and 8–14, 12 μm wide, 1 long apical procercal macroseta present, 1.6–2.2, 
1.9 mm
long, procercus with a comb or partial ring of 4 or more long spines on the procercus and closely appressed to the base of the procercal macroseta, this comb is only visible at 100 × magnification and not visible in all specimens (
Fig. 4E–F
; 
9C,E
); 2 lateral setae at the base of each procercus, 49–78, 66 μm long; supraanal setae 35–88, 65 μm long (n = 5); 8 or more additional setae located on posterior segment. Anal tubules 110–163, 136 μm long with one or two constrictions. Posterior parapods slender, 187–243, 215 μm long.

